<center><table border=0><tr><td><center><H2><font face=arial>These posts are getting way off base from EQ</font></H2></center>
<font face=arial size=2><b>Posted By:</b> <A HREF="/cgi-local/whois2.cgi?TheBlack[BCK]">TheBlack[BCK]</a><br>
<b>Posted On:</b> 3:21 p.m. 9/2/1999<br>
<b>Subject:</b> These posts are getting way off base from EQ<p>
<br><center><img src="http://www.everworld.net/pvpquest/images/divider.gif" width=452 height=22 border=0></center><BR><P ALIGN=CENTER><b>In Reply To:</b> <A HREF="http://www.everworld.net/cgi-local/pvp.cgi?read=391" TARGET=_self>Re: Restricted combat initiation is a Very Bad idea.</A> (wallace)
</STRONG><FONT SIZE=2 color=#FFFFFF FACE=arial>
<P>

<BR>This is Everquest, not UO. This post is not directed at the original poster specifically. I just want to get the idea across that EQ is a different game system and UO ideas on PK/Notoriety/Agressors and such largely do not apply here. There is no justice system and there are no consequences for attacking another PvP player (other than your own death barring faction hits). If you are speaking about EQ faction hits that's a seperate topic and personally I don't mind either way how that gets implemented.
<P>Otherwise what we are disccusing here is
<P>#1 Does EQ use a level limited system to restrict attacks.
<BR>#2 Assuming #1 is yes, how is it implemented for individuals and groups, and when does it apply?
<P>If you answer No to #1, please refrain from muddying the waters in discussions about #2 by trying to re-introduce the concept of eliminating level limits in discussions related to #2. :-P
<P>&gt; I totally agree with this post, but I must add a thought to it.
<BR>&gt; I think it would be very fitting if the aggressor (person that
<BR>&gt; swings first) be held accountable for the attack. By this I mean
<BR>&gt; the attacker must face the consequences of the local justice
<BR>&gt; system. The defender, even if he wins the confrontation, should
<BR>&gt; not suffer an ill effect from the justice system, since all they
<BR>&gt; were doing is defending themselves. Unfortunately this would not
<BR>&gt; account for harassment, where player A harasses player B
<BR>&gt; unrelentingly until player B swings first. Thus player A was
<BR>&gt; really the aggressor. Not sure how to solve this scenario except
<BR>&gt; by (ignoring playername)
<P>&gt; -wallace
<BR>
</FONT></td></tr></table></P>
